    %h3 We know you are addressing these pain points but don't worry we've got your back!!!

    %ul
      %li Traditional e-commerce sites (e.g. Amazon) do not cover local trading.

      %li Traditional marketplaces (Craigslist, Facebook group) do not actually provide beneficial features for local trading, e.g., they cannot visualize the trading nearby you. Also, Facebook marketplace is not well categorized and not easy to access. Craigslist has a really old interface and people don't know how to start.

      %li There is a flurry of items/commodities that go on sale locally on Facebook/Craigslist “buy and sell” groups throughout the semester which usually peaks at the start and end of every semester among student communities. A lot of students tend to buy used/second hand items from these listings that merely a “Facebook post”. The buyers/sellers are not verified sometimes, communication usually becomes very hard between the user and seller and we sometimes have privacy concerns.

      %li Buyer side is also important, but not every app allows people to post their “buy” requests.

      %li Many e-commerce sites require registered accounts (usually paid for selling) to take actions.

      %li Many e-commerce sites do not utilize minimalist designs, taking the user longer time to reach their goals.

      %li Traditional localized trading platforms offer generic templates for buy and sell posts, which puts the responsibility of data representation on the user. Item attributes common to groups of goods are not standardized in most localized trading platforms. A standardized template approach for item categories would streamline viewing posts as the user can become familiar with, for example, 10 templates, as opposed to 10 unique yet jumbled submissions.

      %li Many of the existing options do not map the all the buyer and seller units within a range. It is always convenient for the user to see options visualized on a map to narrow down his options based on various convenience factors.

      %li Communication and privacy are big concerns in local trading. People would like to have a convenient and immediate notification, usually through text messages. However, it is risky to put someone's personal contact on a website directly. It is important to have a proxy to notify people through texts and emails without exposing personal information.

